<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>The imperative mood conveys a command or prohibition directed to the
second or third person. It exists in all voices and in present and
aorist tenses. The negative is μή.</p>
<p>The present imperative is used to command someone to proceed (or not
to proceed) with the action that they were already carrying out. The
aorist imperative is used to command someone to complete the action.
(Rijksbaron 2006, 44-5)</p>
<h2 id="examples-of-imperative-mood-from-papygreek-corpus">Examples of
imperative mood from PapyGreek corpus</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li>καὶ [τ]ὴν [ἐ]ξέδραν <strong>[σκεύ?]ασον</strong> καὶ τὸ τρίκλινον
<strong>στρωθήτω</strong>, [καθ]ὼς Ἀπφὺς θελήση[ι] ἐκ[ε]ῖ γενέσ[]θαι, τὰ
κρόκια καὶ τὰ ἱμάτια <strong>ἐκτίνασσε</strong>·<br>
(kaì tḕn exédran <strong>skeúason</strong> kaì tò tríklinon
<strong>strōthḗtō</strong>, kathṑs Apphùs thelḗsēi ekeî genésthai, tà
kroḱia kaì tà himátia <strong>ektínasse</strong>:)<br>
<em>And make the exedra ready and let the dining room be paved,
according to the arragement Aphys wants; shake out the woollen cloths
and clothes (…)</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/33446">p.mil.vogl.2.77.</a>, 10-13
(sent. 5), transl. Bagnall-Cribiore (2006) p.&nbsp;186.</li>
</ol>
